snippet.textDisplay: This is still undeniably one of the hardest platformers I have ever played, but the soundtrack keeps me coming back to it, not to mention the outright difficult bosses and level design. It's ironic that my mother only bought me two games for the system after my parents divorced, both picked from the discount bin at the video store, both games composed by Tim and Geoff Follin, and both considered relative failures on the system, yet both games share an amazing soundtrack. Although Plok is leaps and bounds a better game than Spiderman and X-Men in Arcade's Revenge

snippet.textDisplay:
This sounds more like Gentle Giant than Genesis. Maybe portions of Selling England-era Genesis (like on "Cinema Show" and "Firth of Fifth"), but this sounds much more like the Power and the Glory, In a Glass House and Free Hand had a baby and it was being played on a SNES.

Portions also sound like Mental Notes-era Split Enz (specifically the longer songs, i.e. "Stranger Than Fiction," "Under the Wheel"), H to He-era VdGG, and Camel during the Mirage days. I keep hearing some Cardiacs influence, but I don't know what specifically. Maybe their slower and less erratic works?

snippet.textDisplay: I remember playing this as a kid and recalling how great the soundtrack was, it was definitely ahead of its time in terms of progressive music on a video game console, I don't think too many people got to appreciate it since either they were too busy playing the game or never played it at all. This was during a time when VGM just wasn't appreciated like it is now, with the internet being able to reach out and show more people.

snippet.textDisplay: What a nice track! Hypnotizing and quite psychedelic. It's effectively progressive rock, yet "videogamish" enough to appeal even to little kids. And those who like prog rock, folk rock and trance can all find a reason to enjoy it. I can hear some Jean Michel Jarre, and the sound at 2:29 slightly reminds me of one of the songs from Terminator 2: Judgment Day for the NES (music by Geoff Follin, pretty damn awesome soundtrack if you ask me). The Follin brothers are epic!
snippet.textOriginal: What a nice track! Hypnotizing and quite psychedelic. It's effectively progressive rock, yet "videogamish" enough to appeal even to little kids. snippet.textDisplay:
Not really. Tim liked them, but said he wanted a stable income, so he left the VGM business forever - which is a huge shame, as he is one of the best composers to ever walk the Earth.
Geoff loved games, and good music - he was Tim's main influence on both fronts. I can't recall why he quit, but I do know none of them hated videogames.
Hell, if you hated the girl next door, would you learn to and then make a three story chocolate cake to give it to her? I think not. Same applies here.
